# GEMINI_API_KEY: Required for Gemini AI API calls.
# AI Studio automatically injects this at runtime from user secrets.
# Users configure this via the Secrets panel in the AI Studio UI.
GEMINI_API_KEY="MY_GEMINI_API_KEY"

# APP_URL: The URL where this applet is hosted.
# AI Studio automatically injects this at runtime with the Cloud Run service URL.
# Used for self-referential links, OAuth callbacks, and API endpoints.
APP_URL="MY_APP_URL"



Have you owned and shipped a feature end-to-end in production (from problem definition to architecture to deployment)?*
Yes, absolutely. I consistently own the entire lifecycle of my projects, moving from initial business requirements directly to database architecture, backend logic, frontend implementation, and final server deployment.
Please describe one feature you personally owned from idea to production?*
The Offline-First Synchronization Engine for Manzoma ERP. Problem: Retail stores frequently lost internet connectivity, completely halting their POS systems and sales. Architecture: I architected a hybrid system to solve this. I built a local desktop POS utilizing SQLite, paired with a cloud PostgreSQL database. I wrote a custom background sync engine in Node.js that securely buffers transactions locally and automatically resolves data conflicts with the cloud the moment the internet is restored. Deployment & Result: I deployed this across a dedicated Linux VPS infrastructure. It resulted in zero operational downtime for store owners and is currently seamlessly processing over 1.5M+ EGP in transaction volume across 3,000+ SKUs.
Have you worked on a product that scaled from early-stage to significant growth (10x+ usage or scale)?*
Yes. I built "Manzoma ERP" from an initial concept to a fully functioning commercial B2B SaaS. It scaled from zero to actively managing 1.5M+ EGP in sales volume and 3,000+ SKUs across multiple retail points. Similarly, I built "CodeKick Academy" (a WebRTC-based LMS) from scratch, launching the complete MVP in just 30 days and immediately scaling to support 40+ active students and concurrent live video sessions. I build architectures designed to handle immediate scaling from day one.
Are you comfortable working across frontend, backend, and infrastructure?*
Completely comfortable. I operate across the entire stack daily. In my recent SaaS projects, I built the frontends (React/Next.js/Flutter), engineered the backends (Node.js/Prisma/Supabase), and managed the infrastructure directly (configuring Linux VPS, reverse proxies, and multi-domain routing). I prefer owning the full vertical slice of a feature rather than being boxed into a specialization.
How do you use AI tools in your development workflow? Explain in detail*
I don't just use AI for basic autocomplete; I use it as an execution engine. My daily drivers are Cursor and Claude Code. Instead of typing out every line, my workflow starts with the architecture. I write very clear specs, define custom skills, and set up automated workflows.  Once the rules are set, I use sub-agents to handle the heavy lifting—like scaffolding UI components, wiring up standard endpoints, or writing boilerplate. Basically, I treat the AI like a team of junior devs. They write the bulk of the code, and my role shifts from being a typist to a code reviewer and architect.  This setup is the exact reason I can build and ship complex SaaS products in just 30-40 days. The AI handles the repetitive stuff, and I save my brain power for the actual hard problems, like offline-first sync logic and DB architecture
